message.content:
We “rolled up” all of the entries that “affect the operating result” (that is, items from sales whose “profit” field already reflects the margin on the sale plus the “interest receivable” items (taken as positive revenue) and then we “net‐off” all the expenses (the “Expense” transactions) plus “Depreciation”. (Many transactions – initial funds, asset acquisitions, purchases and transfers – are balance‐sheet items that do not “flow” into the income statement.) 
Taking the sum over our table we got approximately:

  Sum(sale “profit”)  ≈ 279,378  
  Sum(interest receivables) ≈ 12,370  
  Sum(expense “amount”) ≈ 24,713  
  Sum(depreciation “amount”) ≈ 115,512

Then the net profit used in the cash flow statement is computed as

  Net Profit = (sale profit + interest income) – (expenses + depreciation)
        = (279,378 + 12,370) – (24,713 + 115,512)
        ≈ 291,748 – 140,225  ≈ 151,523

Thus we conclude that the final net profit is about 151522.54.

Accordingly the answer is:
